5302.definition: [ὑστερέω] from {{G5306}}; to be later, i.e. (by implication) to be inferior; generally, to fall short (be deficient)

5304.definition: [ὑστέρησις] from {{G5302}}; a falling short, i.e. (specially), penury

5305.definition: [ὕστερον] neuter of {{G5306}} as adverb; more lately, i.e. eventually

5306.definition: [ὕστερος] comparative from {{G5259}} (in the sense of behind); later

5307.definition: [ὑφαντός] from ὑφαίνω to weave; woven, i.e. (perhaps) knitted

5309.definition: [ὑψηλοφρονέω] from a compound of {{G5308}} and {{G5424}}; to be lofty in mind, i.e. arrogant

5310.definition: [ὕψιστος] superlative from the base of {{G5311}}; highest, i.e. (masculine singular) the Supreme (God), or (neuter plural) the heavens

5311.definition: [ὕψος] from a derivative of {{G5228}}; elevation, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, (specially), the sky, or (figuratively) dignity

5313.definition: [ὕψωμα] from {{G5312}}; an elevated place or thing, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, or (by implication) a barrier (figuratively)

5315.definition: [φάγω] a primary verb (used as an alternate of {{G2068}} in certain tenses); to eat (literally or figuratively)

5316.definition: [φαίνω] prolongation for the base of {{G5457}}; to lighten (shine), i.e. show (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative)

5317.definition: [Φάλεκ] of Hebrew origin ({{H6389}}); Phalek (i.e. Peleg), a patriarch

5318.definition: [φανερός] from {{G5316}}; shining, i.e. apparent (literally or figuratively); neuter (as adverb) publicly, externally

5319.definition: [φανερόω] from {{G5318}}; to render apparent (literally or figuratively)

5320.definition: [φανερῶς] adverb from {{G5318}}; plainly, i.e. clearly or publicly

5321.definition: [φανέρωσις] from {{G5319}}; exhibition, i.e. (figuratively) expression, (by extension) a bestowment

5322.definition: [φανός] from {{G5316}}; a lightener, i.e. light; lantern

5323.definition: [Φανουήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{H6439}}); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an Israelite

5324.definition: [φαντάζω] from a derivative of {{G5316}}; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle)

5325.definition: [φαντασία] from a derivative of {{G5324}}; (properly abstract) a (vain) show ("fantasy")

5326.definition: [φάντασμα] from {{G5324}}; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e. spectre

5327.definition: [φάραγξ] properly, strengthened from the base of {{G4008}} or rather of {{G4486}}; a gap or chasm, i.e. ravine (winter-torrent)

5328.definition: [Φαραώ] of foreign origin ({{H6547}}); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian king

5329.definition: [Φάρες] of Hebrew origin ({{H6557}}); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite

5330.definition: [Φαρισαῖος] of Hebrew origin (compare {{H6567}}); a separatist, i.e. exclusively religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary

5331.definition: [φαρμακεία] from {{G5332}}; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic (literally or figuratively)

5332.definition: [φαρμακεύς] from φάρμακον (a drug, i.e. spell-giving potion); a druggist ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician

5334.definition: [φάσις] from {{G5346}} (not the same as "phase", which is from {{G5316}}); a saying, i.e. report

5335.definition: [φάσκω] prolongation from the same as {{G5346}}; to assert

5336.definition: [φάτνη] from πατέομαι (to eat); a crib (for fodder)

5337.definition: [φαῦλος] apparently a primary word; "foul" or "flawy", i.e. (figuratively) wicked

5338.definition: [φέγγος] probably akin to the base of {{G5457}} (compare {{G5350}}); brilliancy

5339.definition: [φείδομαι] of uncertain affinity; to be chary of, i.e. (subjectively) to abstain or (objectively) to treat leniently

5340.definition: [φειδομένως] adverb from participle of {{G5339}}; abstemiously, i.e. stingily

5341.definition: [φελόνης] by transposition for a derivative probably of {{G5316}} (as showing outside the other garments); a mantle (surtout)

5342.definition: [φέρω] a primary verb (for which other, and apparently not cognate ones are used in certain tenses only; namely,          οἴω;       and ἐνέγκω; to "bear" or carry (in a very wide application, literally and figuratively, as follows)

5343.definition: [φεύγω] apparently a primary verb; to run away (literally or figuratively); by implication, to shun; by analogy, to vanish

5344.definition: [Φῆλιξ] of Latin origin; happy; Phelix (i.e. Felix), a Roman

5346.definition: [φημί] properly, the same as the base of {{G5457}} and {{G5316}}; to show or make known one's thoughts, i.e. speak or say Compare {{G3004}}.

5347.definition: [Φῆστος] of Latin derivation; festal; Phestus (i.e. Festus), a Roman

5348.definition: [φθάνω] apparently a primary verb; to be beforehand, i.e. anticipate or precede; by extension, to have arrived at

5350.definition: [φθέγγομαι] probably akin to {{G5338}} and thus to {{G5346}}; to utter a clear sound, i.e. (generally) to proclaim

5351.definition: [φθείρω] probably strengthened from φθίω (to pine or waste); properly, to shrivel or wither, i.e. to spoil (by any process) or (generally) to ruin (especially figuratively, by moral influences, to deprave)

5352.definition: [φθινοπωρινός] from derivative of φθίνω  (to wane; akin to the base of {{G5351}}) and {{G3703}} (meaning late autumn); autumnal (as stripped of leaves)

5353.definition: [φθόγγος] from {{G5350}}; utterance, i.e. a musical note (vocal or instrumental)

5355.definition: [φθόνος] probably akin to the base of {{G5351}}; ill-will (as detraction), i.e. jealousy (spite)

5356.definition: [φθορά] from {{G5351}}; decay, i.e. ruin (spontaneous or inflicted, literally or figuratively)

5357.definition: [φιάλη] of uncertain affinity; a broad shallow cup ("phial")

5358.definition: [φιλάγαθος] from {{G5384}} and {{G18}}; fond to good, i.e. a promoter of virtue

5359.definition: [Φιλαδέλφεια] from Φιλάδελφος (the same as {{G5361}}), a king of Pergamos; Philadelphia, a place in Asia Minor

5361.definition: [φιλάδελφος] from {{G5384}} and {{G80}}; fond of brethren, i.e. fraternal

5362.definition: [φίλανδρος] from {{G5384}} and {{G435}}; fond of man, i.e. affectionate as a wife

5363.definition: [φιλανθρωπία] from the same as {{G5364}}; fondness of mankind, i.e. benevolence ("philanthropy")

5364.definition: [φιλανθρώπως] adverb from a compound of {{G5384}} and {{G444}}; fondly to man ("philanthropically"), i.e. humanely

5366.definition: [φιλάργυρος] from {{G5384}} and {{G696}}; fond of silver (money), i.e. avaricious

5367.definition: [φίλαυτος] from {{G5384}} and {{G846}}; fond of self, i.e. selfish

5368.definition: [φιλέω] from {{G5384}}; to be a friend to (fond of (an individual or an object)), i.e. have affection for (denoting personal attachment, as a matter of sentiment or feeling; while {{G25}} is wider, embracing especially the judgment and the deliberate assent of the will as a matter of principle, duty and propriety: the two thus stand related very much as {{G2309}} and {{G1014}}, or as {{G2372}} and {{G3563}} respectively; the former being chiefly of the heart and the latter of the head); specially, to kiss (as a mark of tenderness)

5369.definition: [φιλήδονος] from {{G5384}} and {{G2237}}; fond of pleasure, i.e. voluptuous

5372.definition: [Φίλητος] from {{G5368}}; amiable; Philetus, an opposer of Christianity

5374.definition: [Φιλιππήσιος] from {{G5375}}; a Philippesian (Philippian), i.e. native of Philippi

5375.definition: [Φίλιπποι] plural of {{G5376}}; Philippi, a place in Macedonia

5376.definition: [Φίλιππος] from {{G5384}} and {{G2462}}; fond of horses; Philippus, the name of four Israelites

5377.definition: [φιλόθεος] from {{G5384}} and {{G2316}}; fond of God, i.e. pious

5378.definition: [Φιλόλογος] from {{G5384}} and {{G3056}}; fond of words, i.e. talkative (argumentative, learned, "philological"); Philologus, a Christian

5380.definition: [φιλόνεικος] from {{G5384}} and νεῖκος (a quarrel; probably akin to {{G3534}}); fond of strife, i.e. disputatious

5382.definition: [φιλόξενος] from {{G5384}} and {{G3581}}; fond of guests, i.e. hospitable

5383.definition: [φιλοπρωτεύω] from a compound of {{G5384}} and {{G4413}}; to be fond of being first, i.e. ambitious of distinction

5384.definition: [φίλος] properly, dear, i.e. a friend; actively, fond, i.e. friendly (still as a noun, an associate, neighbor, etc.)

5386.definition: [φιλόσοφος] from {{G5384}} and {{G4680}}; fond of wise things, i.e. a "philosopher"

5387.definition: [φιλόστοργος] from {{G5384}} and στοργή (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or children); fond of natural relatives, i.e. fraternal towards fellow Christian

5388.definition: [φιλότεκνος] from {{G5384}} and {{G5043}}; fond of one's children, i.e. maternal

5389.definition: [φιλοτιμέομαι] middle voice from a compound of {{G5384}} and {{G5092}}; to be fond of honor, i.e. emulous (eager or earnest to do something)

5390.definition: [φιλοφρόνως] adverb from {{G5391}}; with friendliness of mind, i.e. kindly

5391.definition: [φιλόφρων] from {{G5384}} and {{G5424}}; friendly of mind, i.e. kind

5393.definition: [Φλέγων] active participle of the base of {{G5395}}; blazing; Phlegon, a Christian

5394.definition: [φλογίζω] from {{G5395}}; to cause a blaze, i.e. ignite (figuratively, to inflame with passion)

5395.definition: [φλόξ] from a primary φλέγω (to "flash" or "flame"); a blaze

5396.definition: [φλυαρέω] from {{G5397}}; to be a babbler or trifler, i.e. (by implication) to berate idly or mischievously

5397.definition: [φλύαρος] from φλύω (to bubble); a garrulous person, i.e. prater

5399.definition: [φοβέω] from {{G5401}}; to frighten, i.e. (passively) to be alarmed; by analogy, to be in awe of, i.e. revere

5400.definition: [φόβητρον] neuter of a derivative of {{G5399}}; a frightening thing, i.e. terrific portent
